# PHASE 3 — KUBERNETES COST VISIBILITY: KUBECOST ON EKS

## COMPLETE SRT — SERIES 3

```srt
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Welcome back to the course.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
In Series one, you built the foundation.
You learned what FinOps is. You learned the three phases.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
You learned unit economics. You built a tagging strategy.
You created your baseline document.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:24,000
In Series two, you found the waste outside the cluster.
You migrated gp2 volumes to gp3.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You released unattached Elastic IPs.
You cleaned up stopped instances.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
You added VPC Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB.
You identified thousands of dollars in monthly waste.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:42,000
That was the low-hanging fruit.
That was Phase one of FinOps. The Inform phase at the AWS account level.

8
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Now it's time to go deeper. Much deeper.

9
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Series three is where we move from account-level visibility
to namespace-level visibility.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:00,000
From service-level cost to pod-level cost.
From guessing which team spent what to knowing exactly which deployment
is wasting money.

11
00:01:00,000 --> 01:06:00,000
Series three is where we deploy Kubecost on EKS.

12
01:06:00,000 --> 01:12:00,000
Before we deploy, let me explain why AWS Cost Explorer is not enough.

13
01:12:00,000 --> 01:18:00,000
AWS Cost Explorer shows you EC2 cost.
It shows you EBS cost. It shows you NAT Gateway cost.

14
01:18:00,000 --> 01:24:00,000
But it cannot answer the question that actually matters
to an engineering team running Kubernetes.

15
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
Which namespace, which deployment, which pod is wasting my money?

16
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
Cost Explorer operates at the AWS resource level.
It does not know about Kubernetes concepts.

17
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
It does not know that ten pods are sharing one EC2 instance.
It does not know which namespace owns which pod.

18
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
It does not know that the llm-ingest deployment requested eight CPUs
and only uses two.

19
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
Kubecost does.

20
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
Kubecost sits inside your cluster.
It watches every pod, namespace, deployment, and persistent volume claim.

21
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
It collects CPU, memory, storage, and network metrics every thirty seconds.

22
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
It combines those Kubernetes metrics with your AWS billing data.

23
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
It calculates exactly how much of each EC2 instance's cost
should be attributed to each pod.

24
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
Then it rolls that up to namespace, team, and service.

25
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
The result. You go from "our EC2 bill is twenty-two thousand dollars"
to "the financial-rag namespace is spending fourteen thousand two hundred dollars
at forty-eight percent efficiency."

26
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
And the llm-ingest deployment is the top contributor.

27
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
That is the difference between guessing and knowing.

28
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
Let me tell you the rest of the story.

29
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
After the waste audit in Series two, that same startup's bill
dropped from forty-seven thousand dollars to thirty-four thousand eight hundred.

30
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
They were thrilled. They thought they were done.

31
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
But inside the cluster, there was more waste. Much more.

32
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
We deployed Kubecost. Within one hour.

33
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
The financial-rag namespace was costing twenty-two thousand dollars per month.
At zero point four eight efficiency. Wasting fifty-two percent of requested compute.

34
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
The riskoracle namespace was costing nine thousand dollars per month.
At zero point six one efficiency. Wasting thirty-nine percent.

35
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Kube-system and monitoring together were costing three thousand eight hundred dollars.

36
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
We applied the rightsizing recommendations.
CPU requests reduced by sixty percent. Memory requests reduced by forty percent.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
Karpenter, which we will cover in Series four,
removed the now-empty nodes.

38
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000
The financial-rag namespace dropped from twenty-two thousand dollars
to fourteen thousand dollars.

39
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Riskoracle dropped from nine thousand dollars to six thousand dollars.

40
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
Combined with Series two savings.
Total bill went from forty-seven thousand dollars to twenty thousand dollars.

41
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
In two series.

42
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
That's what Kubecost delivers.

43
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000
Now let me show you how to deploy it.

44
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Before we deploy Kubecost, you need a few things.
Let me walk through each prerequisite.

45
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
First, you need an EKS cluster.
EKS stands for Elastic Kubernetes Service.

46
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
It's Amazon's managed Kubernetes service.
If you don't have an EKS cluster, pause this video and create one.

47
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
You have several options. You can use the AWS console.
Go to the EKS service, click Create cluster, give it a name.

48
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
Choose a Kubernetes version, choose a role, and click create.
It takes about fifteen minutes.

49
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
You can use eksctl. eksctl is a command-line tool for EKS.

50
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
One command. eksctl create cluster with name finops-cluster,
region us-east-1, nodegroup-name standard-workers, node-type t3.medium, nodes three.

51
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
It takes about fifteen minutes.
You can use Terraform.

52
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
The GitHub repository for this course has Terraform configurations
for financial-rag-agent and riskoracle.

53
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
Clone the repo, run terraform apply,
and you'll have a cluster with both applications deployed.

54
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
That's the best option because you'll have real workloads to optimize.

55
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
Whichever method you choose, make sure your cluster has at least three nodes.
Each node should be at least t3.medium or equivalent.

56
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
You need enough resources to run Kubecost
alongside your applications.

57
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
Second, you need kubectl installed and configured.
Kubectl is the command-line tool for Kubernetes.

58
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
It's how you deploy and manage applications on your cluster.
You use it to create resources, delete resources, view logs, exec into containers.

59
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
Verify that kubectl can talk to your cluster.
Run kubectl get nodes.

60
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
You should see a list of nodes. Each node will have a name,
a status, a role, an age, and a version.

61
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
The status should be Ready.
If you see NotReady, your cluster has problems.

62
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
If you see an error that says "Unable to connect to the server",
your kubeconfig is not configured correctly.

63
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
To configure your kubeconfig, run this command.
aws eks update-kubeconfig with region dollar sign REGION
and name your-cluster-name.

64
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
Replace your-cluster-name with the actual name of your EKS cluster.
This command downloads the cluster's certificate and configures kubectl to use it.

65
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
Now run kubectl get nodes again. You should see your nodes.

66
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
Third, you need Helm installed.
Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes.

67
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
Think of it as apt-get or brew for Kubernetes.
It packages Kubernetes resources into charts.

68
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
A chart can contain deployments, services, config maps, secrets,
persistent volume claims, ingress rules, everything your application needs.

69
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
We're going to install Kubecost using Helm.
The Kubecost chart contains about thirty different Kubernetes resources.

70
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
Without Helm, you'd have to create each one manually.
With Helm, it's one command.

71
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
Verify that Helm is installed. Run helm version.

72
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000
You should see a version number.
If you get an error that says command not found, you need to install Helm.

73
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
On Mac, brew install helm. On Ubuntu, sudo apt install helm.
On Windows, download the installer from the Helm website.

74
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
It takes two minutes.

75
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
Fourth, you need the AWS CLI configured with permissions
to read billing data.

76
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
Kubecost needs to call AWS Cost Explorer to get your account's pricing information.

77
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
It needs to know how much EC2 costs per hour,
how much EBS costs per gigabyte, how much NAT Gateway costs per gigabyte.

78
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000
Without this, Kubecost can only estimate costs based on public pricing.
With it, Kubecost shows your actual costs including discounts,
Savings Plans, and Reserved Instances.

79
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
You should already have this from Series one and two.
You ran aws ce get-cost-and-usage and it returned your total monthly spend.

80
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
If that worked, your AWS CLI is configured correctly.
If not, go back to Series one and fix it.

81
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000
Now you're ready.

82
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
First, add the Kubecost Helm repository.
A Helm repository is a collection of charts.

83
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
The Kubecost repository contains the Kubecost chart
and all its dependencies.

84
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000
helm repo add kubecost https://kubecost.github.io/cost-analyzer/

85
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
You'll see output like kubecost has been added to your repositories.

86
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
Now update your local cache of available charts.
This downloads the latest list of charts and versions from the repository.

87
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
helm repo update

88
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
You'll see output like Hang tight while we grab the latest from your chart repositories.

89
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
Now create a namespace for Kubecost.
Namespaces are how Kubernetes organizes resources.

90
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
They're like folders on a filesystem.
Putting Kubecost in its own namespace keeps it separate from your applications.

91
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
It also makes it easier to clean up later if you need to.

92
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
kubectl create namespace kubecost

93
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
You'll see namespace slash kubecost created.

94
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
Now let's verify the namespace exists.
kubectl get namespaces

95
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
You should see kubecost in the list, along with default,
kube-system, kube-public, and any other namespaces you have.

96
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
Now install Kubecost. This is the main command.
Copy it carefully.

97
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
helm install kubecost kubecost/cost-analyzer
with namespace kubecost

98
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
set kubecostToken equals your email at company.com
set global.aws.enabled equals true

99
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
set global.aws.cloudIntegrationEnabled equals true
set prometheus.server.persistentVolume.enabled equals false

100
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
set kubecostProductConfigs.clusterName equals finops-cluster
set kubecostProductConfigs.currencyCode equals USD

101
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
Let me break down each parameter so you understand
what you're running.

102
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
helm install kubecost tells Helm to install a chart
with the release name kubecost.

103
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
The release name is like a label for this installation.
You can name it anything you want, but kubecost is fine.

104
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
kubecost/cost-analyzer is the chart name.
It's in the kubecost repository we added earlier.

105
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
The chart name is cost-analyzer, but the repository is kubecost.
So together it's kubecost/cost-analyzer.

106
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
dash dash namespace kubecost tells Helm to install the resources
in the kubecost namespace.

107
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
All the pods, services, config maps, secrets,
and persistent volume claims will be created inside this namespace.

108
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
dash set kubecostToken sets a configuration value.
Kubecost uses this token for analytics.

109
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
They want to know how many people are using their software.
It's not required, but it's polite.

110
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
You can use your email address instead of mine.
Use whatever you want.

111
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
dash set global.aws.enabled equals true tells Kubecost
that you're running on AWS.

112
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
This enables AWS-specific features.
It changes the default pricing from GCP pricing to AWS pricing.

113
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000
It enables integration with AWS services.

114
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
dash set global.aws.cloudIntegrationEnabled equals true
tells Kubecost to integrate with AWS's cloud billing APIs.

115
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
This is how Kubecost gets your actual EC2 pricing,
your actual EBS pricing, your actual NAT Gateway pricing.

116
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
Including any discounts, Savings Plans, or Reserved Instances you have.
Without this, Kubecost estimates costs based on public on-demand pricing.

117
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
With this, Kubecost shows your actual costs.

118
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
dash set prometheus.server.persistentVolume.enabled equals false
tells Kubecost not to create a persistent volume for Prometheus.

119
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
Prometheus is the time-series database that Kubecost uses
to store metrics.

120
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
It collects CPU usage, memory usage, network traffic,
and other metrics every thirty seconds.

121
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000
By default, Prometheus stores these metrics on a persistent volume
so they survive restarts.

122
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
But for testing and for this course, you don't need persistent storage.
Setting this to false saves you money on EBS volumes.

123
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
dash set kubecostProductConfigs.clusterName labels all cost data
with your cluster name.

124
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000
This is critical for multi-cluster setups.
If you have dev, staging, and prod clusters, you need to know which cluster
is spending what.

125
12:24:00,000 --> 12:30:00,000
dash set kubecostProductConfigs.currencyCode sets the currency
for cost display. USD is fine.

126
12:30:00,000 --> 12:36:00,000
Now wait for Kubecost to start.
This takes a few minutes.

127
12:36:00,000 --> 12:42:00,000
The first time you install Kubecost, it needs to download container images
from Docker Hub. It needs to start the pods.

128
12:42:00,000 --> 12:48:00,000
It needs to initialize the databases. It needs to scrape metrics
for the first time.

129
12:48:00,000 --> 12:54:00,000
Watch the pods come up.
kubectl get pods dash n kubecost

130
12:54:00,000 --> 13:00:00,000
You'll see several pods. Let me explain what each one does.

131
13:00:00,000 --> 13:06:00,000
The kubecost-cost-analyzer pod is the main Kubecost pod.
It runs the API server, the UI server, and the cost calculation engine.

132
13:06:00,000 --> 13:12:00,000
It's the brain of Kubecost.

133
13:12:00,000 --> 13:18:00,000
The prometheus-server pod runs Prometheus,
the time-series database. It stores all the metrics.

134
13:18:00,000 --> 13:24:00,000
CPU usage, memory usage, network traffic, storage usage, everything.

135
13:24:00,000 --> 13:30:00,000
The kubecost-grafana pod runs Grafana,
a dashboarding tool.

136
13:30:00,000 --> 13:36:00,000
Kubecost includes a pre-configured Grafana instance
with dashboards for cost visualization.

137
13:36:00,000 --> 13:42:00,000
The kubecost-network-costs pod collects network traffic metrics.
It uses eBPF to monitor network traffic between pods
and between pods and the internet.

138
13:42:00,000 --> 13:48:00,000
The kubecost-agent pod collects metrics from the Kubernetes API.
It watches for new pods, deleted pods, scaled deployments, everything.

139
13:48:00,000 --> 13:54:00,000
Wait for all pods to show status Running.
You can watch them in real time with the dash w flag.

140
13:54:00,000 --> 14:00:00,000
kubectl get pods dash n kubecost dash w

141
14:00:00,000 --> 14:06:00,000
The dash w flag watches for changes.
You'll see pods transition from Pending to ContainerCreating to Running.

142
14:06:00,000 --> 14:12:00,000
When all pods are Running, press Ctrl C to exit.

143
14:12:00,000 --> 14:18:00,000
If a pod stays in Pending for more than five minutes,
your cluster might not have enough resources.

144
14:18:00,000 --> 14:24:00,000
Check your node sizes. Check your resource requests.
You might need to add more nodes or use larger nodes.

145
14:24:00,000 --> 14:30:00,000
If a pod stays in CrashLoopBackOff,
something is wrong with the configuration.

146
14:30:00,000 --> 14:36:00,000
Check the pod logs.
kubectl logs dash n kubecost pod-name dash dash previous

147
14:36:00,000 --> 14:42:00,000
Replace pod-name with the actual name of the crashing pod.
The logs will usually tell you what's wrong.

148
14:42:00,000 --> 14:48:00,000
Once all pods are running, port-forward to the Kubecost dashboard.

149
14:48:00,000 --> 14:54:00,000
Port-forwarding creates a tunnel from your local machine
to the Kubecost service inside the cluster.

150
14:54:00,000 --> 15:00:00,000
kubectl port-forward dash dash namespace kubecost
service/kubecost-cost-analyzer 9090:9090 ampersand

151
15:00:00,000 --> 15:06:00,000
This command forwards traffic from port 9090 on your computer
to port 9090 on the kubecost-cost-analyzer service inside the cluster.

152
15:06:00,000 --> 15:12:00,000
It will continue running until you press Ctrl C.
Keep this terminal window open.

153
15:12:00,000 --> 15:18:00,000
Now open your browser. Go to http://localhost:9090.

154
15:18:00,000 --> 15:24:00,000
You are looking at the Kubecost dashboard.
This is your window into Kubernetes cost.

155
15:24:00,000 --> 15:30:00,000
This is the tool that will save you thousands of dollars.
Take a moment to look around. Click on things. Explore.

156
15:30:00,000 --> 15:36:00,000
The first thing to look at is the Allocation page.
Click Allocation in the left menu.

157
15:36:00,000 --> 15:42:00,000
If you don't see the menu, look for a hamburger icon
in the top left corner. Three horizontal lines.

158
15:42:00,000 --> 15:48:00,000
Click it. The menu will slide out.

159
15:48:00,000 --> 15:54:00,000
You'll see a table. Each row is a namespace.
The columns show CPU cost, RAM cost, storage cost, network cost,
and total cost.

160
15:54:00,000 --> 16:00:00,000
There's also an Efficiency column.
That's the most important one.

161
16:00:00,000 --> 16:06:00,000
Here is sample output. Your numbers will be different.

162
16:06:00,000 --> 16:12:00,000
Namespace: financial-rag.
CPU cost: $1,420. RAM cost: $890. Total cost: $2,310. Efficiency: 0.48.

163
16:12:00,000 --> 16:18:00,000
Namespace: riskoracle.
CPU cost: $980. RAM cost: $670. Total cost: $1,650. Efficiency: 0.61.

164
16:18:00,000 --> 16:24:00,000
Namespace: kube-system.
CPU cost: $180. RAM cost: $120. Total cost: $300. Efficiency: 0.45.

165
16:24:00,000 --> 16:30:00,000
Namespace: monitoring.
CPU cost: $95. RAM cost: $65. Total cost: $160. Efficiency: 0.38.

166
16:30:00,000 --> 16:36:00,000
Namespace: kubecost.
CPU cost: $220. RAM cost: $130. Total cost: $350. Efficiency: 0.72.

167
16:36:00,000 --> 16:42:00,000
Let me explain each column.

168
16:42:00,000 --> 16:48:00,000
CPU Cost is the cost of the CPU resources allocated to pods
in this namespace.

169
16:48:00,000 --> 16:54:00,000
Kubecost calculates this by looking at the CPU requests of all pods
in the namespace.

170
16:54:00,000 --> 17:00:00,000
Then multiplying by the cost per CPU core from AWS.

171
17:00:00,000 --> 17:06:00,000
If a pod requests two CPUs, Kubecost allocates the cost of two CPUs
to that pod, regardless of how much CPU the pod actually uses.

172
17:06:00,000 --> 17:12:00,000
That's important. You pay for what you request, not what you use.

173
17:12:00,000 --> 17:18:00,000
RAM Cost is the cost of the memory resources allocated to pods
in this namespace. Same principle.

174
17:18:00,000 --> 17:24:00,000
Storage Cost is the cost of persistent volumes attached to pods
in this namespace.

175
17:24:00,000 --> 17:30:00,000
If a pod has a persistent volume claim for a one hundred gigabyte
EBS volume, Kubecost allocates the cost of that volume
to the pod's namespace.

176
17:30:00,000 --> 17:36:00,000
Network Cost is the cost of network traffic.
Cross-zone traffic. NAT Gateway traffic. Load balancer traffic.
Kubecost tracks it all.

177
17:36:00,000 --> 17:42:00,000
Total Cost is the sum of CPU Cost, RAM Cost, Storage Cost,
and Network Cost.

178
17:42:00,000 --> 17:48:00,000
Now look at the Efficiency column.
This is the most important number on the page.

179
17:48:00,000 --> 17:54:00,000
Efficiency is the ratio of actual usage to requested resources.

180
17:54:00,000 --> 18:00:00,000
Kubecost calculates it by looking at the actual CPU and memory usage
of every pod over the last seven days.

181
18:00:00,000 --> 18:06:00,000
Comparing it to the requested CPU and memory.
And averaging across the namespace.

182
18:06:00,000 --> 18:12:00,000
If a pod requests two CPUs but only uses one CPU,
its CPU efficiency is zero point five.

183
18:12:00,000 --> 18:18:00,000
If it requests two CPUs and uses two CPUs, its efficiency is one point zero.

184
18:18:00,000 --> 18:24:00,000
Kubecost aggregates these pod-level efficiencies up to the namespace level.

185
18:24:00,000 --> 18:30:00,000
An efficiency of zero point seven means seventy percent
of requested resources are being used.

186
18:30:00,000 --> 18:36:00,000
Thirty percent is idle. Thirty percent is waste.

187
18:36:00,000 --> 18:42:00,000
Here's how to interpret efficiency scores.

188
18:42:00,000 --> 18:48:00,000
If your efficiency is below zero point seven,
you are overprovisioning.

189
18:48:00,000 --> 18:54:00,000
You are paying for resources you don't need.
You should reduce your CPU and memory requests.

190
18:54:00,000 --> 19:00:00,000
You can safely reduce them because you have plenty of headroom.
Your pods are not using what they're asking for.

191
19:00:00,000 --> 19:06:00,000
If your efficiency is above zero point nine,
you are underprovisioning.

192
19:06:00,000 --> 19:12:00,000
Your pods are using almost all of their requested resources.
One small spike in traffic could cause CPU throttling
or memory pressure.

193
19:12:00,000 --> 19:18:00,000
Your pods might get killed. Your application might slow down.
You should increase your CPU and memory requests
to give yourself more headroom.

194
19:18:00,000 --> 19:24:00,000
The goal is efficiency between zero point seven and zero point eight five.

195
19:24:00,000 --> 19:30:00,000
Enough headroom for spikes. Not so much headroom that you're wasting money.

196
19:30:00,000 --> 19:36:00,000
This is the sweet spot. This is where you want to be.

197
19:36:00,000 --> 19:42:00,000
Now let's get the same data from the command line.
Because you might want to script this.

198
19:42:00,000 --> 19:48:00,000
You might want to include it in your baseline document.
You might want to automate reporting to Slack or email.

199
19:48:00,000 --> 19:54:00,000
You might want to integrate it into your existing dashboards.

200
19:54:00,000 --> 20:00:00,000
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer dash dash
curl dash s http://localhost:9090/allocation?window=7d&aggregate=namespace

201
20:00:00,000 --> 20:06:00,000
Pipe to jq .data zero to_entries array
get namespace, totalCost, efficiency

202
20:06:00,000 --> 20:12:00,000
Let me break down this command. It's doing several things.

203
20:12:00,000 --> 20:18:00,000
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer
tells kubectl to execute a command inside the kubecost-cost-analyzer pod.

204
20:18:00,000 --> 20:24:00,000
The dash n kubecost specifies the namespace.
deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer specifies the deployment.

205
20:24:00,000 --> 20:30:00,000
Kubectl will pick any pod in that deployment
and run the command there.

206
20:30:00,000 --> 20:36:00,000
The dash dash separates kubectl arguments
from the command to run inside the pod.

207
20:36:00,000 --> 20:42:00,000
Everything after dash dash is the command that runs inside the pod.

208
20:42:00,000 --> 20:48:00,000
curl dash s http://localhost:9090/allocation?window=7d&aggregate=namespace
is the command inside the pod.

209
20:48:00,000 --> 20:54:00,000
It uses curl to call the Kubecost API.
The API endpoint is allocation.

210
20:54:00,000 --> 21:00:00,000
The parameters are window equals 7d for the last seven days
and aggregate equals namespace to group by namespace.

211
21:00:00,000 --> 21:06:00,000
The dash s flag makes curl silent.
No progress meter, no error messages unless something fails.

212
21:06:00,000 --> 21:12:00,000
The pipe symbol pipes the output of curl to jq.
jq is a command-line JSON processor.

213
21:12:00,000 --> 21:18:00,000
It's like sed or awk for JSON.

214
21:18:00,000 --> 21:24:00,000
The jq filter extracts the first element of the data array,
converts it to entries, then for each entry creates a new object
with namespace, cost, and efficiency.

215
21:24:00,000 --> 21:30:00,000
You should see output like this.

216
21:30:00,000 --> 21:36:00,000
namespace financial-rag, cost 2310, efficiency 0.48.
namespace riskoracle, cost 1650, efficiency 0.61.

217
21:36:00,000 --> 21:42:00,000
namespace kube-system, cost 300, efficiency 0.45.
namespace monitoring, cost 160, efficiency 0.38.

218
21:42:00,000 --> 21:48:00,000
namespace kubecost, cost 350, efficiency 0.72.

219
21:48:00,000 --> 21:54:00,000
Now you have cost per namespace from the command line.
This is chargeback-ready data.

220
21:54:00,000 --> 22:00:00,000
You can show each team exactly what they spend.
You can send this to your finance team.

221
22:00:00,000 --> 22:06:00,000
You can include it in your monthly report.

222
22:06:00,000 --> 22:12:00,000
Now let's look at cost by team label.
In Series one, you added a Team tag to all your AWS resources.

223
22:12:00,000 --> 22:18:00,000
You tagged EC2 instances with Team equals financial-rag.
You tagged EBS volumes with Team equals riskoracle.

224
22:18:00,000 --> 22:24:00,000
But Kubernetes doesn't know about AWS tags.
Kubernetes has its own labeling system.

225
22:24:00,000 --> 22:30:00,000
You can add labels to Kubernetes namespaces.
Then Kubecost can aggregate costs by those labels.

226
22:30:00,000 --> 22:36:00,000
First, label your namespaces with the team name.

227
22:36:00,000 --> 22:42:00,000
kubectl label namespace financial-rag team=financial-rag
kubectl label namespace riskoracle team=risktoracle
kubectl label namespace monitoring team=platform

228
22:42:00,000 --> 22:48:00,000
Now verify the labels were added.
kubectl get namespaces dash dash show-labels

229
22:48:00,000 --> 22:54:00,000
You should see team equals financial-rag, team equals riskoracle.

230
22:54:00,000 --> 23:00:00,000
Now query cost by that label.

231
23:00:00,000 --> 23:06:00,000
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer dash dash
curl dash s http://localhost:9090/allocation?window=7d&aggregate=label:team

232
23:06:00,000 --> 23:12:00,000
Pipe to jq data zero to entries array get team, monthlyProjected, efficiency.

233
23:12:00,000 --> 23:18:00,000
The aggregate equals label colon team parameter tells Kubecost
to group costs by the value of the team label.

234
23:18:00,000 --> 23:24:00,000
Kubecost looks at every namespace, finds the team label,
and adds the namespace's cost to that team's total.

235
23:24:00,000 --> 23:30:00,000
You should see output like this.
team financial-rag, monthlyProjected 2310, efficiency 0.48.

236
23:30:00,000 --> 23:36:00,000
team riskoracle, monthlyProjected 1650, efficiency 0.61.
team platform, monthlyProjected 600, efficiency 0.45.

237
23:36:00,000 --> 23:42:00,000
Now you have cost per team.
This is what your CTO wants to see.

238
23:42:00,000 --> 23:48:00,000
This is what your finance team wants to see.
This is what each engineering manager wants to see.

239
23:48:00,000 --> 23:54:00,000
No more guessing. No more spreadsheets. No more manual allocation.
Just data.

240
23:54:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Now let's look at efficiency scores in more detail.
We want to find namespaces that are wasting money.

241
00:00:00,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Add select efficiency less than zero point seven to the jq filter.
This filters out namespaces with efficiency below zero point seven.

242
00:06:00,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Add wastedCPU and wastedRAMGB to see the exact waste.
wastedCPU is requested CPU minus actual usage.

243
00:12:00,000 --> 00:18:00,000
wastedRAMGB is requested RAM minus actual usage in gigabytes.

244
00:18:00,000 --> 00:24:00,000
You should see output like this.
namespace financial-rag, efficiency 0.48,
wastedCPU 3.2, wastedRAMGB 8.

245
00:24:00,000 --> 00:30:00,000
namespace riskoracle, efficiency 0.61,
wastedCPU 1.8, wastedRAMGB 4.

246
00:30:00,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Now you know exactly how much waste is in each namespace.
The financial-rag namespace is wasting three point two CPU cores
and eight gigabytes of RAM.

247
00:36:00,000 --> 00:42:00,000
That's real money. That's resources you're paying for but not using.

248
00:42:00,000 --> 00:48:00,000
Now let's look at rightsizing recommendations.
This is where Kubecost tells you exactly what to change.

249
00:48:00,000 --> 00:54:00,000
Not just you're overprovisioned.
Not just you should reduce your requests.

250
00:54:00,000 --> 01:00:00,000
Specific recommendations. For each deployment.
Current CPU request. Recommended CPU request.

251
01:00:00,000 --> 01:06:00,000
Current RAM request. Recommended RAM request.
Estimated monthly savings.

252
01:06:00,000 --> 01:12:00,000
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer dash dash
curl dash s http://localhost:9090/savings/rightSizing?window=7d

253
01:12:00,000 --> 01:18:00,000
Pipe to jq rightSizing zero to 15 dot array
get namespace, deployment, currentCPU, recommendedCPU, currentRAMGB,
recommendedRAMGB, monthlySavings

254
01:18:00,000 --> 01:24:00,000
Sort by monthlySavings descending.

255
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
Let me break down this command.

256
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
The API endpoint is savings slash rightSizing.
The parameter window equals 7d tells Kubecost to look at the last seven days
of usage data.

257
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
The jq filter takes the first fifteen recommendations.
Then it creates an object with namespace, deployment, currentCPU,
recommendedCPU, currentRAMGB, recommendedRAMGB, and monthlySavings.

258
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
Then it sorts by monthlySavings descending.

259
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
You should see output like this.

260
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
namespace financial-rag, deployment llm-ingest.
currentCPU 8, recommendedCPU 2.
currentRAMGB 16, recommendedRAMGB 6.
monthlySavings 47.20

261
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
namespace financial-rag, deployment vector-db.
currentCPU 4, recommendedCPU 1.5.
currentRAMGB 32, recommendedRAMGB 12.
monthlySavings 89.30

262
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
namespace financial-rag, deployment batch-processor.
currentCPU 4, recommendedCPU 1.
currentRAMGB 8, recommendedRAMGB 3.
monthlySavings 34.10

263
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
namespace riskoracle, deployment risk-calc.
currentCPU 6, recommendedCPU 2.5.
currentRAMGB 24, recommendedRAMGB 10.
monthlySavings 62.40

264
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
These are your optimization targets.

265
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
Kubecost has analyzed the actual usage of every deployment
over the last seven days.

266
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
It calculated the ninety-fifth percentile of CPU usage.
The ninety-fifth percentile of memory usage.

267
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
Then it compared that to the requested resources.
And it gave you specific numbers.

268
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
The llm-ingest deployment requested eight CPUs.
Kubecost saw that the ninety-fifth percentile CPU usage was one point eight cores.

269
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
So it recommends reducing the CPU request to two cores.
That's a seventy-five percent reduction.

270
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
Monthly savings forty-seven dollars.

271
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
Now let's apply these recommendations.

272
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
For the llm-ingest deployment, you would update its resource requests.

273
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
The exact method depends on how you deploy your applications.
If you use Kubernetes YAML files, you edit the file.

274
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
If you use Helm, you update the values.
If you use Terraform, you update the Terraform configuration.

275
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Here's how to patch a deployment directly with kubectl.

276
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
kubectl patch deployment llm-ingest dash n financial-rag
with json patch replace resources requests cpu to 2000m

277
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
replace resources requests memory to 6Gi
replace resources limits cpu to 4000m
replace resources limits memory to 8Gi

278
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000
This command changes the deployment in place.
The deployment will restart.

279
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Watch the rollout.
kubectl rollout status deployment/llm-ingest dash n financial-rag

280
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
The pods will come up with the new resource requests.
The cluster will have more free capacity.

281
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
The Cluster Autoscaler or Karpenter will detect the unused nodes
and remove them. Your EC2 bill will go down.

282
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Now check for CPU throttling after applying.

283
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000
CPU throttling is the silent performance killer.
A pod can be running with no OOMKills but severely throttled.

284
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Requests taking three times longer because the CPU limit is too tight.

285
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
Check CPU throttling ratio.
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/kubecost-cost-analyzer dash dash
curl dash s http://localhost:9090/metrics

286
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
Pipe to grep container_cpu_cfs_throttled_seconds_total

287
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
Or query Prometheus directly.
kubectl exec dash n kubecost deploy/prometheus-server-0 dash dash
wget dash qO dash http://localhost:9090/api/v1/query

288
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
Query rate of container_cpu_cfs_throttled_seconds_total over five minutes
greater than zero point one

289
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
If throttle ratio is greater than zero point one after rightsizing,
the CPU limit is too tight. Increase it.

290
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
Do not increase the request. Increase the limit.

291
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
The distinction between limit and request is critical.

292
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
Requests are what Kubernetes uses for scheduling.
What you pay for in Kubecost.

293
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
Limits are the hard ceiling. What prevents one pod from killing the node.

294
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
Always set limits higher than requests.
A good rule is limits equals two times requests for CPU.
One point five times requests for memory.

295
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
Now let's look at idle costs.
Idle costs are resources that are allocated but not used.

296
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
Pods that are running but not processing requests.
Nodes that are up but have low utilization.

297
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
Add idle equals true to the allocation API.
This tells Kubecost to include idle costs in the response.

298
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
Idle cost is the cost of resources that were allocated but not used.

299
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
You should see output like this.
namespace financial-rag, idleCost 1120
namespace riskoracle, idleCost 640

300
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
The financial-rag namespace has an idle cost of one thousand one hundred twenty dollars.

301
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
That's the cost of resources that were allocated but not used.
That's pure waste.

302
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
That's the money you can save by rightsizing.

303
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
Now let's look at your cluster's overall efficiency.
This is a single number that tells you how well your cluster is utilizing
its resources.

304
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
Aggregate equals cluster.

305
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
You should see a number like zero point five eight or zero point six five
or zero point seven two.

306
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
If your cluster efficiency is below zero point seven,
you have work to do. You are overprovisioning.

307
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
You are paying for resources you don't need.
You should apply the rightsizing recommendations.

308
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
You should reduce your resource requests.
You should let the cluster scale down.

309
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
If your cluster efficiency is above zero point eight five,
you are at risk of performance problems.

310
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
Your pods are using almost all of their requested resources.
One small spike in traffic could cause CPU throttling.

311
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
One memory leak could cause an OOM kill.
You should increase your resource requests to give yourself more headroom.

312
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000
The ideal range is zero point seven to zero point eight five.
This is the sweet spot.

313
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
Enough headroom for spikes. Not so much headroom that you're wasting money.

314
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
Now let's save everything to your baseline document.
You created this document in Series one.

315
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
You updated it in Series two.
Now you're going to add your Kubecost findings.

316
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
echo three equals signs SERIES 3 KUBECOST DEPLOYMENT three equals signs
with date.

317
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
echo dash dash dash COST BY NAMESPACE dash dash dash
then the allocation command with jq.

318
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000
echo dash dash dash CLUSTER EFFICIENCY dash dash dash
then the aggregate equals cluster command.

319
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
echo dash dash dash TOP RIGHTSIZING OPPORTUNITIES dash dash dash
then the rightsizing command with first five results.

320
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
echo dash dash dash TOTAL SAVINGS IDENTIFIED dash dash dash
then the savings endpoint.

321
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000
Now view your updated baseline document.
cat tilde slash finops-baseline.txt

322
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
You should see your Series one baseline,
your Series two waste audit findings,
and your Series three Kubecost findings.

323
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
This document is your complete record.
It shows your starting point, your identified waste,
your visibility improvements, and your rightsizing recommendations.

324
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000
Let's recap what you've built in Series three.

325
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
You deployed Kubecost on EKS.
You have a dashboard that shows cost per namespace,
cost per team, efficiency scores, and rightsizing recommendations.

326
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
You can open http://localhost:9090 anytime
to see your cluster's cost visibility.

327
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
You learned how to query the Kubecost API from the command line.
You can script these queries.

328
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
You can automate reporting. You can integrate cost data
into your existing dashboards.

329
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
You can send cost reports to Slack or email.

330
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
You learned how to interpret efficiency scores.
Below zero point seven means overprovisioning.

331
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
You're paying for resources you don't need.
Above zero point eight five means underprovisioning.

332
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
You're at risk of performance problems.
The sweet spot is zero point seven to zero point eight five.

333
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
You learned how to find idle costs.
Resources that are allocated but not used.

334
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
These are your optimization targets.
These are the dollars you can save.

335
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
You learned how to get rightsizing recommendations.
Kubecost tells you exactly what to change.

336
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
For each deployment. Current CPU request. Recommended CPU request.
Current RAM request. Recommended RAM request. Estimated monthly savings.

337
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
You learned how to apply those recommendations.
Update your deployment YAML.

338
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
Reduce CPU requests. Reduce memory requests.
Let the cluster scale down. Watch your bill drop.

339
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
You now have visibility that AWS Cost Explorer cannot provide.

340
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
Cost Explorer shows you EC2. Kubecost shows you namespace.
Cost Explorer shows you EBS. Kubecost shows you pod.

341
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
Cost Explorer shows you NAT Gateway. Kubecost shows you service.

342
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
This is the difference between guessing and knowing.
This is the difference between hoping your costs are optimized
and knowing they are.

343
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
This is the difference between being a junior engineer who runs commands
and a senior engineer who understands the system.

344
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
Here's what you need before Series four.

345
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
First, Kubecost must be running on your EKS cluster.
Run kubectl get pods dash n kubecost.

346
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
You should see all pods with status Running.
If any pods are not running, check the logs. Fix the issues.

347
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
